whose root beer sprayed all over Maggie Marple,

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:44.520
who jostled Sam,

00:16:44.520 --> 00:16:46.880
who squirted ketchup onto the starched white shirt

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:48.840
of one Mr. Haberford Wilcott,

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:53.840
who had picked just that moment to leave the building.

00:16:53.840 --> 00:16:55.760
And that's how it happened.

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:58.560
Wow, so you slimed the owner

00:16:58.560 --> 00:17:00.480
of a multi-billion dollar corporation?

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:02.840
But anybody could see that it was an accident.

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:04.880
Not Wilcott, apparently.

00:17:04.880 --> 00:17:06.800
I guess he's real particular about his shirt.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:08.880
Well, I'm sure he'll cool off after a few days

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:10.000
and hoping he'll blow over.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:11.880
Yeah, well, I sure hope you're right.

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:15.240
All in all, I'd say you and Samuel had quite a day.

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:18.280
Yeah, I just wish we'd been able to change Wilcott's mind

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:20.160
instead of the color of his shirt.

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:32.530
What a shot!

00:17:32.530 --> 00:17:34.730
What a golf shot!

00:17:34.730 --> 00:17:35.810
Golf on TV.

00:17:35.810 --> 00:17:38.450
The most boring thing yet invented by man.

00:17:38.450 --> 00:17:40.010
Oh, excuse me, sis.

00:17:40.010 --> 00:17:40.850
If you wouldn't mind,

00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:43.410
this happens to be my official clubhouse, remember?

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:45.850
Darling Pines Country Club?

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:49.290
Hate to say it, kiddos, but this is sort of exclusive.

00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:50.370
Meaning what?

00:17:50.370 --> 00:17:53.570
Meaning we don't take too highly to ex-cons.

00:17:53.570 --> 00:17:55.250
Ferguson, we're not ex-cons.

00:17:55.250 --> 00:17:57.330
We were in lockup for like 15 minutes.

00:17:57.330 --> 00:18:00.130
Uh-huh, and Charles Manson was a nice hippie kid

00:18:00.130 --> 00:18:01.290
from Oakland.

00:18:01.290 --> 00:18:03.050
Ferguson, we didn't do anything.

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:04.610
Uh-huh, try writing that line

00:18:04.610 --> 00:18:06.370
on your college applications.

00:18:06.370 --> 00:18:08.250
Extracurricular activities.

00:18:08.250 --> 00:18:09.650
Busting rocks.

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:11.650
Special interests are activities.

00:18:12.370 --> 00:18:14.570
Making license plates.

00:18:14.570 --> 00:18:16.010
Hate to burst or bubble Ferguson,

00:18:16.010 --> 00:18:18.490
but no one here is going to prison.

00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:19.930
Well, this just arrived.

00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:22.330
It's marked county courthouse.

00:18:22.330 --> 00:18:23.530
Well, give me that.

00:18:23.530 --> 00:18:25.570
Wonder what that could be.

00:18:25.570 --> 00:18:26.770
Probably just a letter, you know,

00:18:26.770 --> 00:18:31.860
saying Wilcott dropped the charges.

00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:36.460
Tomb is Clarissa and Darling afternoon of October 19th

00:18:36.460 --> 00:18:39.100
to appearing Cook County Courthouse.

00:18:39.100 --> 00:18:40.860
Sam, they didn't drop their charges.

00:18:40.860 --> 00:18:44.940
We have to go to court.

00:18:44.980 --> 00:18:46.620
In regards to the matter of the people

00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:50.020
versus Clarissa, Darling and Sam Anders?

00:18:50.020 --> 00:18:52.900
Wow, my sister goes to the big house.

00:18:52.900 --> 00:18:55.940
The rock, the pen, the slammer.

00:18:55.940 --> 00:19:00.140
Oh, there is justice in this world after all.

00:19:00.140 --> 00:19:01.860
I never thought we'd get in so much hot water

00:19:01.860 --> 00:19:03.980
just for defending helpless animals.

00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:05.900
Maybe I should go call Jacoby and Myers.

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:07.860
If you get any brilliant ideas, let me know.

00:19:07.860 --> 00:19:11.610
I'll see you, Sam.

00:19:11.610 --> 00:19:14.050
They wouldn't really send us to jail, would they?

00:19:14.050 --> 00:19:15.770
Nah, they couldn't.

00:19:15.770 --> 00:19:16.650
No way.

00:19:16.690 --> 00:19:22.440
It's 90 million years, right?

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:26.440
It was a dirty, lousy, rotten, stinking place to live.

00:19:26.440 --> 00:19:28.480
But that's where we did our living.

00:19:28.480 --> 00:19:33.160
Me, Tess, Mabel, Gertrude, and Frenchie.

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:35.280
We were prisoners of cell block H.

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:37.600
And even though it may not mean much to you,

00:19:37.600 --> 00:19:39.760
it made me proud or in hell.

00:19:39.760 --> 00:19:41.480
Play it, Clarissa.

00:19:41.480 --> 00:19:45.600
Play the one that makes me feel free, deep down inside.

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:46.720
You got it, Frenchie.

00:19:47.680 --> 00:20:02.350
See, we wasn't figuring on staying cooped up

00:20:02.350 --> 00:20:04.630
in that stinking flammable lawn.

00:20:04.630 --> 00:20:08.150
Because me and the gals, we was buzzing out of this joint.

00:20:08.150 --> 00:20:09.310
How long, you suckers?

00:20:09.310 --> 00:20:10.310
Yeah.

00:20:21.500 --> 00:20:22.820
Wow.

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:27.780
I better come up with a plan before Sam and I go up the river.

00:20:27.780 --> 00:20:29.700
Can you believe these articles?

00:20:29.700 --> 00:20:31.620
Tycoon takes on teens.

00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:33.540
Wilcott steamed over stains.

00:20:33.540 --> 00:20:36.700
Makeup magnet makes up bogus charge.

00:20:36.700 --> 00:20:38.100
We're celebrities, Sam.

00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:41.180
I can't believe anyone would really care about us going to court.

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:44.060
I mean, no one cared when we were protesting in the first place.

00:20:44.060 --> 00:20:45.780
Then we were just hot-headed teenagers.

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:53.890
Now we're helpless corporate victims.

00:20:53.890 --> 00:20:56.050
Yes, this is Clarissa, darling.

00:20:56.050 --> 00:20:57.810
Who?

00:20:57.810 --> 00:20:59.730
Yeah, I'll hold.

00:20:59.730 --> 00:21:01.570
It's Mr. Wilcott.

00:21:01.570 --> 00:21:05.100
Don't talk.

00:21:05.100 --> 00:21:06.540
Hello, Mr. Wilcott.

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:07.860
Uh-huh.

00:21:07.860 --> 00:21:09.420
Uh-huh.

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:11.220
Just a sec.

00:21:11.220 --> 00:21:13.620
He says they'll drop the charges on one condition.

00:21:13.620 --> 00:21:15.180
What is it?

00:21:15.180 --> 00:21:17.900
What's the condition?

00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:21.140
Oh, yeah, I understand.

00:21:21.140 --> 00:21:22.580
Just a sec.

00:21:22.580 --> 00:21:26.500
No more protests, no more petitions, no more editorials.

00:21:26.500 --> 00:21:28.300
Sounds like three conditions.

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:29.980
What should we say?

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:31.580
Tell him we'll see him in court.

00:21:31.580 --> 00:21:36.110
How cheap does he think we are?

00:21:36.110 --> 00:21:40.390
Mr. Wilcott, this is our answer.

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:41.830
No way, Jose.

00:21:41.870 --> 00:21:44.550
We're not afraid of you or your big, ugly corporate goons.

00:21:44.550 --> 00:21:46.510
You can press charges till you're blue in the face.

00:21:46.510 --> 00:21:48.550
We're not giving up until you stop testing your products

00:21:48.550 --> 00:21:52.270
on those animals, and that's final.

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:56.230
Uh, Clarissa, you didn't have to get carried away.

00:21:56.230 --> 00:21:58.150
Well, we can't let him bully us around.

00:21:58.150 --> 00:22:00.550
I hear you, but what are we going to do?

00:22:00.550 --> 00:22:01.950
The only thing we can do, we're

00:22:01.950 --> 00:22:03.510
going to stage another protest.

00:22:03.510 --> 00:22:05.510
Yeah.

00:22:05.510 --> 00:22:12.080
But why do I have a funny feeling we're going to regret this?

00:22:12.080 --> 00:22:13.400
Thanks to all this media attention,

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:15.800
we're going to have hundreds of people this afternoon, Sam.

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:17.360
Yeah, and it's great that your mom and dad were

00:22:17.360 --> 00:22:19.200
willing to help us organize this thing.

00:22:19.200 --> 00:22:20.240
Yeah.

00:22:20.240 --> 00:22:22.640
Oh, and the folk guitars from Cafe Let It Be

00:22:22.640 --> 00:22:24.920
is going to lead us in a medley of protest songs.

00:22:24.920 --> 00:22:26.720
And don't forget the Thomas Tupper Dance Club's

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:29.320
interpretive ballet, celebrating the life cycle

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:30.880
of the spotted owl.

00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:32.560
Yeah, I'm not sure how that one fits in,

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:34.000
but I guess they mean well.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:35.760
Is this a protest or what?

00:22:35.760 --> 00:22:37.720
Yeah, this time Wilcott won't be able to ignore

00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:39.200
what we have to say.

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:41.920
Hey, guys, these signs look great.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:43.080
Thanks.

00:22:43.120 --> 00:22:45.600
So, uh, how do we look?

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:47.280
Excellent, Mr. and Mrs. Darling.

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:48.160
Can I keep that, Mule?

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:49.360
Yeah, totally cool.

00:22:49.360 --> 00:22:50.720
So is everything all set?

00:22:50.720 --> 00:22:53.240
Yep, this is one major protest underway.

00:22:53.240 --> 00:22:55.120
Great, we're just going to make some sandwiches in case

00:22:55.120 --> 00:22:57.800
anyone gets hungry out there.

00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:00.000
Yeah, I always work up quite an appetite myself

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:01.120
at these rallies.

00:23:01.120 --> 00:23:04.040
Come on, let's go make our protest pita specials.

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:09.970
Boy, your parents are really into this protest thing.

00:23:09.970 --> 00:23:13.010
Yeah, I guess it's kind of a second honeymoon for them.

00:23:13.010 --> 00:23:15.050
So are the bullhorns ready?

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:17.650
Ready and raring to go.

00:23:17.650 --> 00:23:19.650
Two, four, six, eight.

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:21.650
Who do we wish to debate?

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:25.050
Wilcott, Wilcott, Wilcott!

00:23:25.050 --> 00:23:29.770
Clarissa Darling, how lovely to see you again.

00:23:29.770 --> 00:23:33.730
And your little friend Sam, of course.

00:23:33.730 --> 00:23:36.650
Now, about this little protest you've got cooking.

00:23:36.650 --> 00:23:38.850
Actually, it's turned into a pretty big protest,

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:39.810
Mr. Wilcott.

00:23:39.810 --> 00:23:41.570
Yeah, and if you've come here to talk us out of it,

00:23:41.570 --> 00:23:42.290
forget it.

00:23:42.290 --> 00:23:43.730
We're committed to our cause.

00:23:43.770 --> 00:23:47.730
Oh, indeed, and I admire that commitment.

00:23:47.730 --> 00:23:50.810
We at Wilcott Industries are nothing if not committed.

00:23:50.810 --> 00:23:54.810
You two teens give me hope for the youth of America today.

00:23:54.810 --> 00:23:55.850
Well said, sir.

00:23:55.850 --> 00:23:56.770
We do.

00:23:56.770 --> 00:24:00.370
Why, if I had a daughter, I'd want her to be just like you.

00:24:00.370 --> 00:24:02.050
You do have a daughter, sir.

00:24:02.050 --> 00:24:03.330
Oh, right.

00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:05.010
Well, I hate to interrupt, but we've

00:24:05.010 --> 00:24:07.490
got a protest to get to in about 10 minutes.

00:24:07.490 --> 00:24:08.410
Join us if you like.

00:24:08.410 --> 00:24:11.410
I think you know the address.

00:24:11.410 --> 00:24:13.770
It's very funny.

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:16.170
Yes, well, I don't think that little protest

00:24:16.170 --> 00:24:17.250
is going to be necessary.

00:24:17.250 --> 00:24:19.050
Big protest.

00:24:19.050 --> 00:24:20.730
And we think it is necessary.

00:24:20.730 --> 00:24:24.570
You see, kids, how can I say this?

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:27.330
The tradition thing, sir, they've opened your eyes.

00:24:27.330 --> 00:24:29.650
Oh, yes, you've opened my eyes.

00:24:29.650 --> 00:24:32.970
We at Wilcott Industries have a tradition to uphold.

00:24:32.970 --> 00:24:36.130
A tradition that was begun with my father's father.

00:24:36.130 --> 00:24:38.530
Haverford, Wilcott I, may he rest in peace, sir.

00:24:38.530 --> 00:24:41.330
My point is, you and your friends

00:24:41.330 --> 00:24:45.810
Steve here have made me see it's time to move forward.

00:24:45.810 --> 00:24:48.290
All Wilcott products are pure, natural,

00:24:48.290 --> 00:24:50.570
environmentally friendly, and completely

00:24:50.570 --> 00:24:52.490
free of animal testing.

00:24:52.490 --> 00:24:53.850
What, since when?

00:24:53.850 --> 00:24:55.530
Since now.

00:24:55.530 --> 00:24:56.810
We won?

00:24:56.810 --> 00:25:00.050
I like to think we all won, Steve,

00:25:00.050 --> 00:25:03.010
including the cute little furry animals.

00:25:03.010 --> 00:25:05.010
Especially the bunnies, sir.

00:25:05.010 --> 00:25:06.530
I'm sure they'll be glad to hear it.

00:25:06.530 --> 00:25:09.290
Well, let's get going to that press conference.

00:25:09.290 --> 00:25:10.090
Press conference?

00:25:10.090 --> 00:25:11.170
Of course.

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:13.930
You're going to want to be there for our big announcement.

00:25:13.930 --> 00:25:16.250
Wilcott Industries takes leadership role

00:25:16.250 --> 00:25:18.130
in protecting animal rights.

00:25:18.130 --> 00:25:19.970
I guess this means we're not going to jail.

00:25:19.970 --> 00:25:22.730
Oh, don't be silly.

00:25:22.730 --> 00:25:24.570
Do we really have to drop those charges?

00:25:24.570 --> 00:25:25.690
Yes, sir, the legal teams.

00:25:25.690 --> 00:25:26.930
Oh, never mind.

00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:29.050
Of course you won't be going to jail.

00:25:29.050 --> 00:25:30.490
After all, you've opened our eyes

00:25:30.490 --> 00:25:32.570
to a great marketing strategy.

00:25:32.570 --> 00:25:34.690
Wilcott goes green.

00:25:34.690 --> 00:25:36.970
It's a million-dollar idea if I ever heard one.

00:25:36.970 --> 00:25:39.170
It should be our most profitable marketing campaign

00:25:39.170 --> 00:25:39.690
ever, sir.

00:25:39.690 --> 00:25:41.250
Not now, Penny Baker.

00:25:41.250 --> 00:25:43.530
Oh, so you're doing this all for profit.

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:46.970
OK, everybody smile.

00:25:46.970 --> 00:25:49.490
I'll get this out with a press release immediately, sir.

00:25:49.490 --> 00:25:50.610
Just look at them.

00:25:50.610 --> 00:25:52.290
The hope of America.

00:25:52.290 --> 00:25:58.090
Why, the hope of the whole country, the whole planet,

00:25:58.090 --> 00:26:02.730
Wilcott Industries, for the future, for the planet,

00:26:02.730 --> 00:26:05.170
for the furry ones, sir.

00:26:05.170 --> 00:26:07.490
Come on, Penny Baker, let's get out of here.

00:26:07.490 --> 00:26:08.610
See you there, kids.

00:26:08.610 --> 00:26:11.250
Be proud.

00:26:11.290 --> 00:26:13.410
So we did it.

00:26:13.410 --> 00:26:15.810
Yeah, but I thought victory was supposed to feel good.

00:26:15.810 --> 00:26:17.770
Yeah, I feel so cheap, so used.

00:26:17.770 --> 00:26:19.570
So exploited.

00:26:19.570 --> 00:26:22.370
But you know, Steve, I guess sometimes when

00:26:22.370 --> 00:26:23.970
you can't change people's minds,

00:26:23.970 --> 00:26:26.010
you have to settle with changing their ways.

00:26:26.010 --> 00:26:30.960
That's gonna be the funny, Sam.

00:26:30.960 --> 00:26:31.920
Sure.

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:32.880
Here.

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:34.360
Thanks.

00:26:34.360 --> 00:26:37.880
Heck of a guy that, Wilcott, very engaging gentleman.

00:26:37.880 --> 00:26:39.360
How would you know?

00:26:39.360 --> 00:26:42.400
Oh, we just spent a lovely morning on his private links.

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:44.000
You play golf with Wilcott?

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.840
Well, let's just say I facilitated his game.

00:26:47.840 --> 00:26:49.480
Sounds like you were his caddy.

00:26:49.480 --> 00:26:50.280
So?

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:52.360
Man's caddy is more than a club carrier.

00:26:52.360 --> 00:26:54.920
It's a personal advisor.

00:26:54.920 --> 00:26:56.480
Confidant.

00:26:56.480 --> 00:27:00.240
Yeah, next thing you know, I'll be sitting in on board meetings.

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:01.000
It's possible.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:05.000
They do need someone to hand out the pencils.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:05.960
No way.

00:27:05.960 --> 00:27:07.000
What?

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.240
This is worth a major response.

00:27:09.240 --> 00:27:12.200
They reduced the print size of Calvin and Hobbes.

00:27:12.200 --> 00:27:14.480
I guess it's worth some sort of protest.

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:17.120
But do we really want to go through all that?

00:27:17.120 --> 00:27:18.320
Come on, Sam.

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:44.170
What's the worst that could happen?

